@node sourcecode "Baking Powder!"
@prev history
@next credits

Before I go on to talk about the stuff @{u}I@{uu} wrote, I must give some credit to a couple people who helped me (without their knowledge) make DogFight! as fluid as it is.

   1 - The person at C= who wrote the DoubleBuffering example included in the MaxonC++ demos section; DogFight! would not exist without that sourcecode.
   2 - Micheal D. Bayne, the author of Gershneblanker.  I blatently stole the FastSQRT code directly out of the ASwarm module sourcecode.
   3 - Dave Schreiber, author of DSound.  I also took parts of the Audio.device allocation routines from his DSound sourcecode.

Thanx to all of you mysterious strangers.


I've included the sourcecode.
   
This was a difficult decision for me.  There are several reasons why I shouldn't have, and few reasons why I should.  In any case, it's done, and I'll try to explain why I think I shouldn't (which should help you in compiling it yourself).

   @{b}1@{ub} - This was an (almost) overnight hack, and I (initially) didn't think that any more than 4 people would see it.  As such, it contains a number of problems inherent to hacks:
      @{u}A@{uu} - I didn't comment it as much as I should have.
      @{u}B@{uu} - The code is somewhat hectic.  Well, @{i}all@{ui} code is hectic, regardless of what the CIS professors say.  But DogFight! @{u}really is@{uu} a Frankenstein program, so good luck.

   @{b}2@{ub} - Oh, yea... @{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub} In case you didn't notice, this is @{u}C++@{uu} code.  I know that I may not write the ideal OOP code, but I @{u}do@{uu} use C++ features.  Therefore, this program needs to be compiled with a C++ compiler (unless you @{u}really@{uu} change the sourcecode).

   @{b}3@{ub} - I @{u}still@{uu} have absolutely no documentation on how to program the Amiga.  No RKMs, nix.  Everything I use in my programs I derived from other sourcecodes, or learned from MaxonC++'s HotHelp.  @{u}Do Not consider this code as an example of Correct Programming of Amiga Specific Functions!!@{uu}

Those are not nearly all of my fears and reasons for hesitating to release the sourcecode.  However, ultimately, I live on examining other's code, and if only one person benefits from this, it was worth it.  And perhaps someone will bother to debug and improve it before I get around to it.


@{b}Developement environment@{ub}

DogFight! was developed on a 1-year old german Amiga 4000/030.
It has been tested on:
   ¤  A4000/030-25MHz 5MB RAM, 80MB HD
      NEC MultiSync 3D
   ¤  A3000 68030-25MHz 8MB RAM, several HDs
      NEC MultiSync 2D
      OmniBus graphics card

@endnode

